## 🐛 Bug Report

After adding a row, I iterate through the cells of that row to replace their content (a boolean value to a checkmark or an X) and format them accordingly (align to center, then change font color to green or red depending on the boolean value).
The value is updated correctly, but the style changes appear in every cell.
There seems to be no way to correct this. Even if I try to format the other cells back to their desired format, it has no effect.

Lib version: 4.4.0

## Steps To Reproduce

```
const workbook = new exceljs.Workbook();
const worksheet = workbook.addWorksheet('bugdemo');

const columns = ['Col 1', 'Col 2', 'Col 3', 'Col 4', 'Col 5'];
worksheet.columns = columns.forEach(column => ({
                    header: column,
                    key: column,
                    width: 30
}));

const worksheetContent = [
  {
    "Col 1": "Some value",
    "Col 2": "Some other value",
    "Col 3": false
  },
  {
    "Col 1": "Some value",
    "Col 2": "Some other value",
    "Col 3": false,
    "Col 4": 34,
    "Col 5": "cucumber"
  },
  {
    "Col 1": "Epstein didn't kill himself",
    "Col 3": true,
  }
];

worksheetContent.forEach(row => {
  const currentRow = worksheet.addRow(row);
  currentRow.eachCell({ includeEmpty: true }, (cell) => {

    cell.style = serviceSettings.formatting.rows.style;
    cell.alignment = serviceSettings.formatting.rows.alignment;

    if (typeof cell.value === 'boolean') {
      cell.value = cell.value ? 'YES' : 'NO';
      cell.alignment = {
          vertical: 'top',
          horizontal: 'center'
      };
      cell.style.font.color = {
         argb: cell.value ? 'FF00FF00' : 'FFFF0000'
      }
   }
  });
});
```

## The expected behaviour:
Individual cells containing a boolean value should receive a new string value, `YES` or `NO` (this works).
They must also be horizontally centered, and red or green, depending on their boolean value (this doesn't work!)

## Possible solution (optional, but very helpful):
```
¯\_(ツ)_/¯
```

